    {
      "_id": "ctUXT9PkkmfQMIS1",
      "name": "Reality Adjacent",
      "type": "feat",
      "system": {
        "source": {
          "custom": "",
          "book": "ToB2",
          "page": "34",
          "license": ""
        },
        "description": {
          "value": "<div class=\"rd__b  rd__b--3\"><p>The aurora horribilis does not fully exist in physical space. If the aurora is subjected to an effect that allows it to make a saving throw to take only half damage, it instead takes no damage if it succeeds on the saving throw, and only half damage if it fails.</p><div class=\"rd__spc-inline-post\"></div><p>In addition, attack rolls against it have disadvantage. A creature with &amp;Reference[rule=truesight] doesn't have disadvantage on its attack rolls, but if that creature looks at the aurora, it must succeed on a [[/save ability=wisdom dc=16]] saving throw or be &amp;Reference[condition=incapacitated] with a speed of 0 for 1 minute. An &amp;Reference[condition=incapacitated] creature can repeat the saving throw at the end of each of its turns, ending the effect on a success.</p><p>This trait is disrupted while the aurora is &amp;Reference[condition=incapacitated] or has a speed of 0.</p></div>",
